    <div class="highlight">
        <p><strong>Key Insight</strong>: Social work can bridge gaps between migrants, communities, and the diaspora, fostering inclusivity and resilience in a polarized world.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Conclusion: A Path Forward</h2>
    <p>India in 2025 is a nation of immense potential and profound challenges, where economic growth and social tensions coexist. The rise of Hindu nationalism, economic disparities, and geopolitical frictions shape a landscape that profoundly impacts Gen Z, driving many to seek opportunities abroad. While Indian immigrants face cultural and racial challenges in Western countries, their contributions—both to host nations and India—are undeniable. The 35-million-strong diaspora stands as a pillar of India’s global influence, offering economic, political, and cultural support critical for the nation’s 2047 development goals. Social work, with its commitment to justice and community, is poised to play a transformative role by supporting migrants, engaging the diaspora, and addressing polarization through education, advocacy, and inclusive programs. By harnessing the energy of its youth and the expertise of its diaspora, India can navigate its challenges and emerge as a global leader, fostering a society that balances progress with unity.</p>

